{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.71,0.25,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine removal and replacement of her subdermal contraceptive implant, which was inserted three years ago. She has no concerns with the device and wishes to continue with this form of contraception. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The implant is not palpable in the usual insertion site on the medial aspect of her upper arm, despite careful examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blind exploration of insertion site","Insertion of new implant adjacent to previous site","Ultrasound localisation and gynaecologist referral","X-ray of the upper arm","Magnetic resonance imaging"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common clinical scenario where a subdermal contraceptive implant cannot be palpated at the time of planned removal. The implant may have been inserted too deeply, migrated, or in rare cases, may not have been inserted at all.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound localisation and gynaecology referral\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. High-frequency ultrasound can accurately locate non-palpable implants and mark their position for removal. Referral to an experienced gynaecologist is recommended as deep implant removal may require specific expertise and equipment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlind exploration\u003C/strong\u003E of the insertion site is inappropriate and potentially harmful. Without knowing the exact location of the implant, blind exploration could cause tissue damage, nerve injury, or vessel damage, and is unlikely to be successful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the upper arm\u003C/strong\u003E is not the imaging modality of choice. While the implant is radio-opaque, X-ray cannot provide the precise three-dimensional localisation needed for safe removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary and overly complex for this situation. Ultrasound is the preferred imaging modality as it is readily available, cost-effective, and provides excellent visualisation of the implant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of new implant\u003C/strong\u003E adjacent to the previous site would be inappropriate before removing the existing implant. This could lead to double dosing of progestogen and would make future removal more complicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of this situation involves careful documentation of insertion depth and location, ensuring superficial subdermal placement during insertion, and confirming both provider and patient can palpate the implant after insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-palpable subdermal contraceptive implants require ultrasound localisation prior to removal.","Deep or migrated implants should be referred to an experienced clinician for removal.","Documentation of implant insertion site and depth is crucial for future removal."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 30]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T18:57:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T18:58:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda